{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "regulation service participation requirements BPM Market Operations",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "1c8ee8f3-b671-4441-b754-10e3b0ea44b7",
        "score": 0.6304982,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for Market Participants involved in CRR (Congestion Revenue Rights) trading within the CAISO (California Independent System Operator) markets. It emphasizes the need for these participants to maintain comprehensive risk management frameworks that address credit, liquidity, and market risks. Participants must have written policies and procedures approved by their governing bodies and demonstrate adherence to industry risk management standards.\n\nAdditionally, Market Participants must have adequate personnel and procedures to respond to CAISO communications, including handling invoices and collateral requests. The document also specifies that CRR Holders or Candidates must submit risk management policies and controls to CAISO, ensuring they align with accepted practices. Any modifications to these policies require prompt submission to CAISO for review. Participation in CRR markets is contingent upon CAISO's acceptance of these risk management practices.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Credit_Management_&_Market_Clearing/page_22.jpg",
          "page_num": 22,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Credit Management & Market Clearing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "93c01c4f-2389-4f03-b6f8-6cd4567b9994",
        "score": 0.59410286,
        "text": "The document outlines the participation requirements for Market Participants in the CAISO Markets. Key points include:\n\n1. **Direct Participation Requirements**: \n   - Participants must have a net worth of $1 million, total assets of $5 million, or credit support from a guaranty or Letter of Credit from a qualified entity.\n   - Participants who no longer meet these requirements must notify CAISO and cease participation.\n\n2. **Minimum Participation Requirements**:\n   - Participants must provide certified statements (Officer Certification Forms), adhere to risk management policies, and meet capitalization requirements.\n\n3. **Certified Statements (Officer Certification Forms)**:\n   - Participants with a direct financial relationship with CAISO must submit an annual Officer Certification Form.\n   - The initial form is required during the registration process, and updates are due by April 30 each year.\n   - Failure to submit the form results in suspension from the CAISO Markets until compliance is met.\n\n4. **Certification Criteria**:\n   - Participants must certify that they have undergone appropriate training related to transaction volume and risk, as specified in the CAISO Tariff.\n\nThe document emphasizes compliance with financial and procedural standards to maintain market participation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Credit_Management_&_Market_Clearing/page_21.jpg",
          "page_num": 21,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Credit Management & Market Clearing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "149cb1d7-d31e-42b3-b172-eaa1bbfa431c",
        "score": 0.56171143,
        "text": "The document is a section from the CAISO Business Practice Manual focused on the Credit Policy Overview. It outlines:\n\n1. **Credit Policy Overview**: \n   - Details who is subject to the credit policy and its goals.\n   - Explains the principles of credit policy operation.\n   - Provides contact information for questions regarding the credit policy.\n   - Offers an overview of the sections in the BPM.\n\n2. **Credit Policy Applicability and Goal**:\n   - All Market Participants requesting transmission services with CAISO must meet specific participation requirements.\n   - Participants must adhere to the credit policy as per Section 12 of the CAISO Tariff.\n   - The policy aims to protect Market Participants from undue financial risk.\n\n3. **Minimum Criteria for Direct Participation**:\n   - Participants must qualify as an \"appropriate person\" or \"eligible contract participant\" as per the Commodity Exchange Act.\n   - They must be involved in generating, transmitting, or distributing electric energy.\n   - Alternatively, they can participate as a Scheduling Coordinator, provided they are not involved in certain other roles and are engaged in providing necessary electric energy services.\n\nThese requirements are in addition to the Minimum Participation Requirements, and most entities can meet them by fulfilling one or more specified conditions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Credit_Management_&_Market_Clearing/page_20.jpg",
          "page_num": 20,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Credit Management & Market Clearing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "56666689-ce8e-493f-94fc-cb89233b814f",
        "score": 0.55906796,
        "text": "The document outlines the participation of a PDR-LSR (Proxy Demand Resource - Load Shift Resource) in energy markets, focusing on functionalities for BTM (Behind-The-Meter) storage. Key points include:\n\n1. **Participation and Resource IDs**: \n   - PDR-LSR can participate in Day-Ahead and Real-Time Energy markets using two Resource IDs: Load Curtailment (CUR) and Load Consumption (CON).\n   - CUR is eligible for Resource Adequacy (RA) and Ancillary Services (AS), needing to meet the Net Benefit Test (NBT) price threshold.\n   - CON is ineligible for RA and AS, with bids required to be below $0.\n\n2. **Load Curtailment Products**:\n   - PDR and RDRR (Reliability Demand Response Resource) are focused on load curtailment, excluding energy export measurements.\n\n3. **Net-Energy Metered (NEM) Locations**:\n   - NEM locations can participate in PDRs and RDRRs, but data must only reflect load or load offset using the MGO (Metered Generation Output) methodology.\n\n4. **Meter Data Intervals**:\n   - For locations with net energy export, meter data must be set to zero when using a Customer Load Baseline.\n   - Meter data should reflect energy output up to, but not including, export levels, especially when calculating Generator Output Baseline.\n\nOverall, the document details the operational and regulatory framework for PDR-LSR participation in energy markets, emphasizing compliance with specific bidding and data management rules.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Demand_Response/page_15.jpg",
          "page_num": 15,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Demand Response",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e034cf64-46a2-4f8d-b184-0059e71df663",
        "score": 0.55854285,
        "text": "The document page outlines specific sections related to energy market operations:\n\n1. **Non-Participating Loads (2.1.7):** Scheduling Coordinators (SCs) can submit bids for Non-Participating Loads in the Day-Ahead Market (DAM) to procure energy. These bids may represent aggregated loads and must be scheduled at an Aggregated Pricing Node. Non-Participating Loads cannot be bid to be curtailed in the Real-Time Market (RTM).\n\n2. **Utility Distribution Companies (2.1.8):** A Utility Distribution Company (UDC) owns a distribution system for energy delivery and provides regulated retail electricity services to eligible customers. UDCs serve customers not eligible for direct access or those choosing not to use an alternate retailer. UDCs must have an operating agreement with the California Independent System Operator (CAISO).\n\n3. **Metered Subsystems (2.1.9):** A Metered Subsystem (MSS) is a contiguous electricity system within an Existing Zone Generation Trading Hub, operating as a utility for years before CAISO operations. It includes municipal utilities, water districts, and other agencies, and is integrated into the CAISO grid. MSSs must have CAISO-certified meters and operate under an MSS Agreement. To participate in CAISO markets, MSSs must be represented by SCs, which can be the MSS itself.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_44.jpg",
          "page_num": 44,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

